The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite advanced and our operators offer virtually all services as their partners in Western Europe.
Still, we are missing something here - a virtual operator that would force the classic ones to discount.
Maybe he won't be missing long.
About the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe, we have written many times on Mobil.cz.
Furthermore, the Czech Republic also confirmed that the price of SMS is higher than that of the rest of the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming charges, there may be a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really wants to go into battle.
It may sound paradoxical, but we have three mobile networks and a penetration rate of over 100 percent.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, like to say that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this, the President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ) Pavel Dvorák, who in the past expressed several times that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It’s probably true that a classic operator with its own network doesn’t seem to have a chance anymore (in other words, it would hardly have been looking for a frequency).
But there is another option - a virtual operator.
It was precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that brought a significant reduction in prices, to which classical operators had to respond.
Even before Tesco Mobile and Virgin Mobile entered the market, there were similar voices in the UK.
However, it turned out that the place for such operators is and can be really successful.
We don’t have to go too far for examples.
In February this year, we informed you about the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, more than 100,000 customers managed to get this operator and become the fifth-largest operator there.
The financial group Penta, which owns U:fona in the Czech Republic, is behind Mobilking.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to be able to function effectively, they need much less customers than a classic operator.
They do not carry relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
In the world, virtual operators tend to be low-cost, offering cheap calls and SMS, which is often balanced by a narrower offer of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can be a pretty good move and a bet on an untapped target group.
This operator focuses specifically on men.
“Administrative men choose Mobilking - an operator they like and can trust,” says David Seibertz CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether a concept similar to that in Poland could be caught with us.
Vodafone press spokesperson Miroslav Čepický doubts this: “The Czech market is relatively small for segmental access, on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated in terms of service offerings.
In the Czech Republic without a chance, mobile operators say
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual mobile operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
“We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic, the negotiations do not look very hopeful.
Rather, there will be the launch of Mobilking in other countries of our region,” said Jana Studničková, a press spokesman for the financial group Penta in a telephone interview with Mobil.cz.
Indirectly, it confirmed that the existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not inclined to do so.
Rather, it tries to do everything possible to ensure that no potential competitor is created.
For a long time, the GTS Novera group has not been hiding in the interest of launching a virtual mobile operator, which would like to take the next step to become a real competitor of the O2 Telephony in the field of corporate customers.
We are very interested in offering our customers not only solid, but also mobile telecommunications services.
The sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly discussed this option with all Czech mobile operators.
We have already made progress with some of them in the negotiations,” said Pavel Kaidl, a press spokesperson.
Maybe it’s going to be better times.
From unofficial information, the first virtual operator seems to be expected by the end of the year.
For now, however, its creation is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
At this point, we do not think that there is room on the Czech market for the creation of a full-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market is very specific to other markets.
So far, we have not been approached by any entity with a comprehensive and serious project in this area,” Vlastimil Srseň, of the Press Department Telephonics O2, said in his statement to Mobil.cz.
Other operators refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
Press spokesperson Martina Kemrová supplies in rare agreement with the statement O2: “We have not yet seen any viable and mutually beneficial business project on which it would be possible to build more”
He adds: “It’s hard for a virtual operator to appear in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
At this point, we would already have had a specific deal on the table in order to be able to think in this short term -
Vodafone vampires its attention to meet the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický says: “By negotiating with potential virtual operators, we are open, especially in the area of cost-sharing and infrastructure.
This is what we consider the most beneficial in terms of customers.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner for building a shared network for fast mobile internet -
Responsible authorities - with operators one hand
The procedure of mobile operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to a decrease in prices and thus a decrease in their profits.
Why make it easier for such a competitor?
The fact that when it comes to operators, they are able to pull a rope behind it, also testifies to the drag around the formation of U:phone.
Probably the biggest pressure towards the Czech Republic was at the time of U:fone’s formation from T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly available information from the ČTÚ website.
Now, however, U:fon is useful as an argument why not allow a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová said: “The competitive environment of the mobile market has recently been enhanced by the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
In view of the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that the entry of another player would impose high demands on him and, above all, on his services -
Due to this approach, mobile operators are directly striking the absolute lack of interest of the Czech regulatory authorities.
It is not only a question of the position of ČTÚ, which unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike Great Britain and other developed countries - does not have the power to interfere in competition.
These belong exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Competition (UOHS).
However, he took a typical stance on the whole issue.
The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible after the conclusion of a contract between the mobile operator and the virtual operator on the lease of the necessary infrastructure.
