Prague’s public transport will be driving on the chip for the first time on Wednesday.
Wednesday 1 October 2008 will be entered into the history of the Prague Transport Company as the date on which the first passengers will enter the metro, tram and buses, which will have an electronic coupon in their pocket instead of the paper ticket.
At this point, you can buy about 100,000 people who own an Opencard chip card.
Travellers can purchase a 30-day and 90-day and annual coupon (which will be valid from 1 January 2009) and at the same time have it uploaded to their chip card in the info centers and workplaces of the Transport Company in the metro stations of the Museum, Mostek, Railway Station Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Paradise Garden, Kacherov and Luka.
Coupons can also be bought online from yesterday at the website of the Transport Company www.dpp.cz.
The service was used by over four hundred customers in the afternoon.
Those who start using the online store can definitely forget about the outlet window in metro stations, where they had to stay regularly in long queues for paper tickets.
The coupon will be purchased online and recorded on the Opencard card at one of the 13 branches of the Municipal Library.
“In these places, there is a bar for passengers with trained staff to help those interested in online shopping and also upload a coupon purchased on their card,” said Martin Opatrný, a spokesperson for the project.
In addition to libraries, it will be possible to upload electronic coupons to Opencard also in self-service vending machines, which are mounted in several metro vestibules.
What do these machines look like?
They are red, resembling ticket markers, and may have already been noticed by passengers in the metro stations Roztyly, Budejovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
“There are five in the city now, but by the end of the year there should be 80 of them,” he added.
The coupon checks the driver's seat automat
The service of machines that start working tomorrow is simple.
Simply insert the Opencard chip card into it and the previously paid coupon will be uploaded to it itself.
Electronic coupons from tomorrow are valid not only in the capital, but also in its surroundings.
Thus, in suburban trains and bus lines with the number 300 to 499, which is driven to the capital mainly by the inhabitants of Central Bohemia.
“In trains included in the Prague Integrated Transport, the guides are equipped with card readers to determine the time and zone validity of coupons,” explained Filip Drápal, a company that compiles the timetables of Prague’s public transport.
The suburban buses have card readers built in the cash register with the driver.
It is therefore necessary to show not only the chip card to the driver, but also to attach the Opencard to the designated place on the side of the cashier.
This will check the validity of the recorded coupons.
“If a passenger needs to verify the validity of the recorded coupons, there is nothing easier than asking the driver for this information,” Drápal added.
Passengers who do not drive by suburban buses and will not remember when their coupon expires can return to self-service vending machines where coupons on the card are recorded.
Here, information about the validity of their documents will be displayed on the instrument display.
