The Ministry of the Interior requires that a driver with three administrative sanctions for driving under the influence of alcohol must install a system in his car that prevents him from starting the car in drunkness or if he does not breathe.
The proposal entered knowledge already in June this year and is now included in the annual report of the Supreme Public Prosecutor’s Office, according to which it is a pilot project that will last for one year.
Its aim is to return the driver behind the wheel, so drivers will also have to take the course of re-education.
In addition to the National Office for Transport Safety, the Directorate-General of Transport (DGT) and the Foundation of the Institute of Technology for Car Safety (FITSA) will also participate in this experience.
According to statistics, between 30 and 75 per cent of automakers charged more than once during drunk driving will re-occupation behind the wheel.
Alcolock should prevent this because it is a vehicle-connected system that measures alcohol levels in the ventilated air and prevents the car from starting if the driver does not breathe before or if a higher concentration of alcohol is recorded than the permitted concentration.
Its price is over 1 000 euros and would have to be paid by the guilty man himself.
A study conducted in this sense in the US in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with this equipment had been reduced by 65% during the first year since the introduction.
In Spain, 115 people are expected to save their lives every year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: that this behaviour be addressed before it results in a criminal offence.
And in order to help its introduction, since legislation can be done in the usual way, the necessary adjustment of criminal provisions requires a change in the law.
The equipment is not yet available on the Spanish market in any sales version, although some industrial vehicles and public service vehicles have already been tested.
