Interview - Blood, which is again certain
Hema-Québec celebrated the tenth anniversary of the founding, and his president, Dr. Francine Décary, rightly rejoiced because Hema-Québec became one of the most reliable and effective blood suppliers in the world.
First of all, he regained the trust of the public, who was seriously shocked after a scandal with contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is commonly known, the state blood reserve administered by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Department was contaminated by the immune deficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In view of this drama and wave, the Canadian government launched a public investigation in February 1994, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, which was intended to explain the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and formulate recommendations that such a disaster should not be repeated.
While Judge Krever was stunned to report, some provinces launched a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Québek, the Gélinea Committee held this role.
After Gélineau and Krever's report, two suppliers were established in Canada: Hema-Québec, which was to be managed by Quebec, and the Canadian Blood Society for the Supply of All Provinces and Both Territories.
“When Hema-Québec started its activities in 1998, almost 38% of people still had confidence in the quobec blood system,” Décary said.
“The situation was depressing.
By continuing to increase the safety of blood products and continuous work in this area over the years, we have regained public confidence,” he said and proudly adds that at the beginning of 2008, Hema-Québek trusted almost 94% of the Québek population.
Dr. Décary, however, does not lose sight of the fact that 'trust is something very fragile'.
Since its establishment on September 28, 1998, Hema-Québec has applied the principle of prudence.
“We have seen many cases of human disease of mad cows in Europe, new variants of the disease called Creutzfeldt-Jakob’s disease,” says a woman who has been leading the company since its inception in 1998.
“We didn’t know if this disease could spread through blood.
Therefore, one of the basic recommendations of Kreverov and Gélineau’s report, according to which, where we do not know this and when there is a serious disease at stake, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob’s disease, which is characterized by brain degeneration inevitably leading to death, it is necessary to take exclusive measures.
In April 1999, we therefore rejected blood from people who have stayed in the UK for more than one month since 1980.
A few years ago, it was safely proven that this disease was transmitted by blood.
So this episode showed us that keeping to the principle of prudence made sense.
In 1999, a much more accurate technique appeared on the market to detect HIV: tests with nucleic acid (NAT) that allow the donor blood to detect the presence of the virus itself, rather than the presence of antibodies on which the tests used before were based.
The NAT tests allowed to shorten the deaf period between the moment of the patient’s infection and the moment when our first viruses may be revealed by our blood technicians, the specialist explains.
We were able to shorten this period to less than a week.
We have significantly reduced the risk that some donors could be infected without knowing about it and without being able to figure it out.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of getting AIDS through blood transfusions.
The risk of getting HIV-contaminated blood is now exposed to one in 12 million people.
In other words, it means that before someone becomes infected with HIV, 12 million blood products will have to be distributed.
Since Hema-Québec distributes 400,000 to 500,000 blood products annually, it will take 24 years before the first case of HIV transmission occurs through the blood product.
I think we can get or prescribe a blood transfusion needed for healing today,” said Héma-Québek, head of management.
“The challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
We never know which disease element can appear in the system.
Just last year, a chiungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted to the blood by the banging of insects.
It is necessary to be constantly cautious,” continues Dr. Décary, stressing that in addition to safe supply, Hema-Québec must also count on sufficient supply.
“The needs are growing because the population is getting older.
As a result of more aggressive cancer treatment, patients often need a new dose of red blood cells or platelets.
Population ageing also has consequences for a blood donor network, which, on average, consists of only 3% of Québecians allowed to donate.
Any healthy person aged at least 18 years, corresponding to the criteria of admissibility, but can donate blood only once every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
14% of people offering blood are not on average accepted because, for example, AIDS or malaria wearers, and if they have visited a country where mud fever is ordered, they are excluded for one year.
With this 3%, we can maintain a state that meets the needs of hospitals.
Deficiencies are very rare.
However, members of the donor network need to be supplemented in proportion to how they age and can no longer donate blood.
However, it is difficult to convince people to give blood, especially to keep and encourage them to become regular donors.
Life is so unbridled today that we rarely find an hour to donate blood,” said Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissue, such as bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs and skin, which is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before they are stored at Hema-Québek, which also manages the only public blood bank from the umbilical cord in Québek.
The umbilical cord, which was previously considered to be biomedical waste, dries blood rich in stem cells that can serve to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
“A few weeks ago, we celebrated the deposit of our thousand blood samples from the cord into the bank, and we assume that we will take them over a thousand a year.
In the beginning of next year, we should start offering them for transplants,” explains Dr. Décary, who describes the blood collection program from the cord as very popular.
“Some mothers are disappointed that they don’t have access to it, because Hema-Québec doesn’t have enough resources to offer this comprehensive and expensive program to all hospitals in Quebec.
