Opinions - Orwellian discourse by Barrick Gold
In September 17, Le Devoir published a letter to Patrick J. Garver, executive vice president of the Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
With Orwellian logic, he confirms that the world’s largest gold producer has launched the prosecution of three authors and a poor small publishing house for insulting honor in order to trigger a “transparent public debate” and demands six million.
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, they do not judge truth, especially in the case of prosecution for insult to honor, but the law.
It’s no surprise that Garver completely overlooks this fundamental resolution.
Or is it the best way for Barrick Gold to lead a public debate to the disappearance of anyone who dares to defend the opposite position?
Whatever the process, authors and publishers of the book Noir Canada (Black Canada) will be forced to spend respectable amounts in order to be prepared to defend themselves and fight in a very unbalanced fight with the army of lawyers supported by the almost idyllic pockets of the mining company.
Tactics in these unbalanced struggles often consists in the destruction of the defendants in order to enforce the conciliatory proceedings that will clog the mouth of the counterparty and, moreover, will scare anyone who would dare to devote himself to the matter.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, she should have taken a look at the whole thing in public opinion.
Contrary to what is happening in several countries where Barrick Gold operates, in Canada there is a debate under normal circumstances in the exchange of ideas, and not in the wounds with a collar.
Therefore, mining companies were not enough to open their books, document their documentation, and to create a real debate through newspapers, media, publications, and the financing of independent scientific teams that could bring light to the whole thing.
Barrick Gold, however, seems to have no confidence in public opinion, and he rejects petitions and letters to support the authors of Noir Canada.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he could demand a “public debate” and also disdain the same public’s views?
It seems that this word in the vice president’s world refers only to fat-paid lawyers, and not all Canadians; this is a rather narrow concept of this concept.
They have the right to speak in democracy.
Barrick Gold doesn't understand - or doesn't want to understand - that the public, who supports the authors and publishers of Noir Canada, is doing so mainly because they refuse the brutal ways of mining society.
The public is ready to hear and assess the matter, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, not in the context of what many see as prosecutions, in which the defendant is to be clogged by mouth (in the context of his prosecution of a public debate, Barrick has by the way just called on the authors of Noir Canada to officially notify them that they should stop using this term...).
If we miss the surreal Garver speech, the prosecution initiated by Barrick Gold is a direct attack on university freedom of inquiry and the search for truth that is essential to every democratic society.
In total, it denies the right to quote credible sources and to discuss facts and interpretations that constitute the very basis of intellectual activity.
If, in a country like Canada, it is impossible to study and discuss topics that do not like the rich companies of this world without exhibiting ourselves to repeated prosecution, who else will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could be created by following the scientific norms used by Noir Canada authors.
He has the right to answer.
The university environment we belong to has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold’s excessive action makes it clear that, despite what he claims, he has no desire to lead a transparent debate.
For the university world, this is a loss, as well as for the public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to introduce measures that would restrict such an type of unfair prosecution.
