The psychology of trumping: why do we spend more money?
At auctions, customers are willing to spend more money, overestimate goods.
Neurological and economic foundations of this well-known - and seemingly irrational - behavior has been revealed to researchers in the field of neurology and economics of the University of New York.
According to their study, published in the journal Science, people do not want to be late in the eBay auction competition, so they prefer to pay too high a price.
The study, using an experimental auction, attempted to map the scheme of this ‘game’ in the nervous system.
One group of volunteers was betting, the other group participated in a playful auction, using the functional magnetic resonance (fMRI) method to study the active areas of the brain of experimental persons.
In both games, the participants could win money, but when playing at an auction, the important element of which is to knock the other side, the whole under the cerebral cortex, called striatum, began to function intensively during the loss.
This brain area, in addition to many other functions, plays a role in the “self-rewarding” mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, it is possible to explain the screw-up of the price by trying to avoid a sharp strike reaction.
To support their theory, members of the research team from a number of economists conducted a financial cross-sectional investigation.
Under different conditions, three groups were charged against one partner.
The control group was simply told what the real value of a given product is, and they made bets.
In addition, other members of the group were promised that if they left the game they would be awarded $15 more.
On the contrary, the third group received $15 before the auction, but in the event of a loss, its members lost that money.
The difference between the two groups was, therefore, everywhere in the fact that one was highlighted by the win and the other by the loss.
The members of the group playing against the loss, however, were willing to go higher than in the control and “winner” group, which confirms the hypothesis of neurologists.
These results cannot be derived from any previously existing economic theory.
For they have so far explained the phenomena noticeable in auctions of joy of victory and avoidance of risk.
“When neurological imaging methods helped us solve the contradiction between these two theories by now reaching the third explanation,” said Andrew Schotter, a professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When to seek a doctor?
About half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infections, and in Hungary, this chronic liver disease is listed among the main causes of death.
The number of domestic cases of hepatitis infection is estimated to be 100 thousand, but only 7,000 of them are treated. The cause of this is that the sick often do not know that they are infected.
The name of hepatitis is a summary name for infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
In their symptoms there are many similarities, a symptom is inflammation of the liver and jaundice, but the originators of the disease and their caused disease differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses are spread in two main ways, depending on the origins of the disease: hepatitis A and E by digestive organs (for example, infected foods, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses of blood and body fluids (sperma, vaginal secret, saliva).
Travellers should in any case be protected by vaccination against virus A and B, there is no vaccine against type C virus.
Symptoms of hepatitis A occur two to three weeks after ingestion of an infected meal, usually accompanied by nausea, weakness, abdominal problems, urge to vomiting.
Then on the skin and eye whites form jaundice, light stools and darken urine. Treatment can take up to two to three weeks.
Every year, a million people die from a more serious type of the disease, liver cancer and hepatitis B.
The main cause is that, according to estimates, only every tenth infected drug is treated.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if not treated, it can lead to liver circus or liver cancer.
Most infected with their disease do not even know the originator of the disease destroys the liver cells in a bad way, and so the first symptoms appear in many cases in 20-30 years.
Therefore, it is very important to timely prevention, implementation of regular signings.
In three groups, this disease occurs much more frequently than on average: among people who had had a blood transfusion before 1991, between drug users and people with tattoos.
Currently, the estimated worldwide number of subjects infected with chronic hepatitis C 200 million.
Since the disease can already demonstrate a routine laboratory examination, a person should contact his or her practical doctor if he or she notices any symptom of unknown origin.
In early detection, the disease is treatable, the virus can be removed from the body, preventing infection and preventing cancer.
September 30 is a world day of hepatitis, which was first organized worldwide by organizations representing the sick.
Its aim is to highlight the chronic inflammation of the liver caused by these viruses, the causes of its formation and the importance of early detection of the disease.
Who believes in God doesn’t hurt so much?
According to the results of recent research, faith in God works as a certain analgesic, which could have facilitated death to Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University conducted an interesting experiment, examining how faith in God affects pain perception, according to the British daily Telegraph.
As part of a rather bizarre survey, 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists were subjected to electric shocks, while all observed a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to rule out much of the pain.
Thanks to a detailed study of the human brain, Catholics have also been able to activate the part of their brain that is responsible for regulating pain.
Research is the first in a series of researches, which scientists, philosophers and theologians from different parts of the university participate alongside academics.
The test was carried out precisely by attaching a sparking tool to the left hand of the experimental entity, which issued electric shocks.
The researchers asked the participants of the attempt to carefully observe two paintings: Sassoferrat's Virgin Mary from the 17th century and Lady with the edge of Leonardo da Vinci, painted in the 15th century.
The authors of the research hoped that the view of the Virgin Mary would create a certain state of piety in the believers, while da Vinci’s paintings were chosen because they were not too different from the first and were acting in a calming sense.
Experimental subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner and during this time they received in four consecutive parts of 20 electroshocks, while separately watching the image with a religious or general theme.
The Catholics stated that when they looked at the Virgin Mary, they felt “safe” as if they were “careed” and “relaxed,” they were fulfilled by peace.
When watching a religious theme picture, they felt 12 percent less pain than when they had Leonard’s work before them.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who has also participated in the research, believes that a similar effect can be achieved by any strongly impressive image even in atheists, only the right photograph must be found.
