Smart car imitates flight of bumblebee
What would be the best method of developing technologies capable of preventing collisions, if not imitations of detectors of obstacles occurring in the world of nature?
For example, at the bee.
The initial strategic idea of a surprising project, presented at the Japanese CEATEC trade fair, was introduced to engineers from Nissan by bumbledoers. It was about how to build a new generation of collision prevention systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has constructed a biomimetic BR23C-type robotic control system, a robotized mini-car equipped with bee characteristics, with the ultimate goal of helping to create a system that can eliminate all precipitation.
“In the course of the flight, each bee creates its own personal space of oval shape, which is in fact very similar to our safety packaging,” explained Kazuhiro Doi, CEO of the brand for the field of technological PR and R&D.
Folded eyes play an important role, allowing bees to see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the folded eye, engineers reached after the idea of a laser telescope.
It identifies obstacles at a distance of up to 2 meters before BR23C in the 180-degree field of vision, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately turns into an operation to prevent collisions.
The obstacle is captured within a fraction of a second, then the robotized car starts to imitate the movements of the bee and by turning the wheels to the extent necessary to prevent the collision immediately changes the direction.
Unlike any existing system, this elusive maneuver takes place in a completely instinctive way.
“If that were not the case, the robotic car would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshijuki Ando, Head of the Mobility Laboratory and Robotic Car Project.
It must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology meets the most vulnerable and internal layer of safety protective packaging, within which precipitation is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what the bees do to avoid other bees.
This process must not take longer than a wink of the eye.
However, unlike bees, this movement cannot be directed up, down or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and only in a direction that can be rotated.
Instead of endless options offered to bees, only the possibility of rotating, acceleration and slowing were applied in the case of a robotic car.
BR23C uses lithium-polymer accumulators that are lighter and have a higher energy density, meaning they have a longer lifespan than lithium-ion variants.
According to Ando, instinctive, intelligent reactions are important, not the processing ability, the less data storage.
This mechanism must process and respond only to a few incoming signals per second.
It is not necessary to store and react using intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, so it uses only memory of a few kilobytes.
It doesn't need memory with giga- or megabyte capacity.
This is the first step towards developing technology for immediate avoidance, which, according to Nissan’s estimate, could reach mass-produced vehicles within ten years.
Another possibility of application may be a connection between the unit and the GPS satellite navigation system, which, after avoiding obstacles, would lead the motorist to the ultimate goal.
